              <tr>
                <td bgcolor="#ECECEC" valign="top"
 nowrap><b><font color="#000000" face="arial" size="2">akrim</font></b></td>
                <td bgcolor="#ECECEC" valign="top"><font color="#000000" face="arial" size="2"><small>Posted&nbsp;-&nbsp;06/19/2003&nbsp;: 2:02:37 PM</small><hr size="2"><span class="spnMessageText"> Assume you are in a dungeon where almost everything assists (most dungeons) and assume you want to pull single mobs (most of us like that). Understanding how mobs transmit aggro to each other is very important to your ability to use the CoS to pull singles.<br />Assume that there are two mobs side by side (call them A & B) and you cast a spell on mob A.  Mob A then has direct hate on you and due to proximity is probably going to transfer that hate to mob B.  Mob B will have indirect hate on you.  Every mob that comes within a certain distance of Mob A (who has direct hate) will inherit that hate and if you are close to them, they will come for you.  That means your ability to pull singles will be virtually nil.  Lets look at mob B though, since it has only indirect hate against you, it will pursue but it will not transfer that hate to other mobs that it comes into contact with.  So if you can avoid direct hate of other mobs, you can pull mob B anywhere you want without creating a train.  The key to using the CoS is that it allows you to avoid creating direct hate by being invisible....you can run by all sorts of mobs that don't see invis and you won't cause them to aggro.  Now if mob A (remember mob A?) is chasing you, it will transfer its hate to all those mobs you ran by anyway, so they're gonna chase you...but mob B (good ole mob B with indirect hate) can chase you all over the place and you don't have to worry about it transferring its hate and causing other mobs to aggro provided that you don't make them aggro yourself.  So the ideal situation works like this....<br /><br />You're deep in the dungeon of your choice with your suspended pet or party stationed back at your camp spot and you want to pull mob B to them.  You want to create direct hate on mob A and bring it near to mob B and then immobilize mob A.  Then you hit your CoS and run back through all the things between you and your camp.  If you have ran far enough, mob A won't chase you when the root/mez wears off.  Since it doesn't chase, it doesn't cause other mobs to aggro you.  Mob B does chase you but it doesn't make other things it passes aggro due to it only having indirect hate.  And finally since you are invisible to the other things, you don't aggro them yourself....you arrive back at your camp with the chosen target on your heels and nothing else...you are the star puller.</span></font></td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td bgcolor="#e9e9e9" valign="top"
 nowrap><b><font color="#000000" face="arial" size="2">GenmaTheMonk</font></b></td>
                <td bgcolor="#e9e9e9" valign="top"><font color="#000000" face="arial" size="2"><small>Posted&nbsp;-&nbsp;06/19/2003&nbsp;: 1:35:11 PM</small><hr size="2"><span class="spnMessageText"> Feign death suspends you from the aggro list, with a slight chance to clear you from the aggro list.<br /><br />If only a single mob is aggroed, and that mob does not naturally see through invis/itu, then being invis/itu when you stand will keep you in the 'suspended aggro' state as far as the mob is concerned.<br /><br />If you are very far away when invis breaks, the mob may decide not to chase you and you then only have 'latent aggro' as far as the mob is concerned -- it may transfer aggro to other mobs if it social, and it may chase after you if you get within range.<br /><br />There are a variety of tricks that can be used with this knowledge.<br /><br />-- Genma, 65 Monk, Lanys T'Vyl</span></font></td>
